<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  WiX v4 source for DeployCoreRemoteAgent.msi.

  The MSI is a thin wrapper: it drops the canonical installer script
  (Install-DeployCoreAgent.ps1, copied from backend/app/services/
  remote_agent_install.ps1 at build time by the CI workflow) into Program
  Files and runs it once, passing the SERVERURL and ENROLLTOKEN properties
  straight through. All the real work (downloading/installing the stock
  RustDesk client, configuring it headless, enrolling) lives in that script,
  so the MSI and the copy-paste one-liner install path stay identical.

  The script is NOT run directly from a custom action. Two confirmed reasons,
  found the hard way across two real failures:

  1. The script itself invokes a second, nested msiexec.exe (to install the
     bundled RustDesk client) - per Microsoft's own _MSIExecute Mutex docs
     ("set only while processing the InstallExecuteSequence table"), that
     mutex is held for this WHOLE table, so a custom action running inside it
     cannot safely launch another msiexec.exe of its own.
  2. Custom actions of type deferred/commit (what any elevated, WixQuietExec-
     based action here is) can ONLY be scheduled between InstallInitialize and
     InstallFinalize - confirmed via Windows Installer Error 2762 ("the action
     must be scheduled between InstallInitialize and InstallFinalize") when
     this file first scheduled its single agent-install action AFTER
     InstallFinalize. That positioning is what actually produced the
     detail-free MSI 1603 on the very first real deployment test (this error
     fires immediately, matching the fast ~46s failure observed) - not a
     mutex conflict, which was a reasonable but wrong first guess, and not
     the target VM's internet access, which was also fine.

  The fix for both: the custom actions below (scheduled after InstallFiles,
  a valid position, not after InstallFinalize) register a Scheduled Task (as
  SYSTEM, triggered ONSTART - see its own comment for why not ONCE) and
  immediately trigger it too, then return right away - the outer MSI finishes
  normally in moments, and the actual RustDesk install + enrollment runs
  seconds later from Task Scheduler, fully outside any MSI transaction,
  sidestepping the mutex concern too.

  The MSI also bundles the DeployCore-branded tray companion (DeployCoreTray.exe)
  and its icon (deploycore.ico) - both produced by CI from remote-agent/tray/,
  drawn from the same mark as the browser favicon - and starts the tray in each
  user's session at logon. The one-liner install path does NOT include the tray;
  the .msi is the full branded package.

  It ALSO bundles the stock RustDesk client installer itself
  (rustdesk-x86_64.msi, fetched by CI from RustDesk's own GitHub release) so
  the install script never needs outbound internet on the target machine -
  confirmed necessary after the first real deployment-pipeline test: a
  provisioned VM with no internet access failed with a bare MSI 1603 and no
  detail, traced to this download failing. The one-liner path still downloads
  it (a human runs that with their own internet, normally).

  NOTE: MSI custom-action sequencing is exactly the kind of thing that needs
  validating on real Windows - the CI workflow builds this, but the first
  green build should be smoke-tested on a throwaway VM. The PowerShell
  one-liner shown on the Remote Management tab is the guaranteed path and
  depends on none of this.
-->
<Wix xmlns="http://wixtoolset.org/schemas/v4/wxs">
  <!-- CI passes -d BuildVersion=1.0.<run number>.0 so every published build
       has a genuinely higher ProductVersion than the last (MajorUpgrade
       below only fires on a real version increase) - defaulted here only for
       a manual/local `wix build` with no -d given. A static version here was
       a real, confirmed bug: re-running `msiexec /i` for what Windows
       Installer considered "the same product, same version" (even after the
       files had been manually deleted rather than properly uninstalled) was
       silently treated as a no-op/repair rather than a fresh install -
       RegisterAgentTask/RunAgentTask's own `Condition="NOT Installed"` (see
       below) then evaluates false, and nothing happens: no error, no log,
       no new enrollment attempt. -->
  <?define BuildVersion="1.0.0.0" ?>
  <Package
      Name="DeployCore Remote Management Agent"
      Manufacturer="DeployCore"
      Version="$(var.BuildVersion)"
      UpgradeCode="6f3d1c2a-9b7e-4d51-8a2c-2e6f4b1d9a30"
      Scope="perMachine">

    <MajorUpgrade DowngradeErrorMessage="A newer version is already installed." />
    <MediaTemplate EmbedCab="yes" />

    <!-- DeployCore icon on this MSI's own Add/Remove Programs entry. Generated
         by the tray app's export-icon mode and staged next to this .wxs by CI. -->
    <Icon Id="DeployCore.ico" SourceFile="deploycore.ico" />
    <Property Id="ARPPRODUCTICON" Value="DeployCore.ico" />

    <!-- Passed by the deployment pipeline / the tab's install command:
         msiexec /i DeployCoreRemoteAgent.msi /qn SERVERURL="https://..." ENROLLTOKEN=xxx -->
    <Property Id="SERVERURL" Secure="yes" />
    <Property Id="ENROLLTOKEN" Secure="yes" />
    <!-- SKIPRUN=1 installs the package (files + sequencing) WITHOUT running the
         agent-install custom action - lets CI smoke-test that the MSI itself is
         valid and installable without needing a live DeployCore server. -->
    <Property Id="SKIPRUN" Secure="yes" />

    <StandardDirectory Id="ProgramFiles64Folder">
      <Directory Id="INSTALLFOLDER" Name="DeployCore Remote Management Agent">
        <Component Id="InstallScript" Guid="*">
          <File Id="InstallPs1" Source="Install-DeployCoreAgent.ps1" KeyPath="yes" />
        </Component>
        <!-- The Scheduled Task's target (see this file's own header comment
             for why the task exists at all): a thin batch launcher rather than
             pointing schtasks /tr straight at powershell.exe keeps that
             command's own quoting shallow and simple. Takes no arguments -
             see AgentParams below for why. -->
        <Component Id="RunScript" Guid="*">
          <File Id="RunAgentInstallCmd" Source="RunAgentInstall.cmd" KeyPath="yes" />
        </Component>
        <!-- SERVERURL/ENROLLTOKEN, written via WiX's own native IniFile
             action - not passed as Scheduled Task command-line arguments.
             Confirmed necessary live: CI's smoke test only ever verifies the
             /tr command is REGISTERED with the right text (SKIPRUN=1 never
             actually runs it) - it can't verify Task Scheduler re-parses a
             deeply nested-quoted /tr string back into the right arguments at
             ACTUAL execution time, and a real deployment showed exactly that
             gap: the agent script produced no log at all, consistent with it
             receiving an empty enroll token and failing before ever writing
             one (see remote_agent_install.ps1's own top-of-file ordering
             fix). Writing these to a plain file removes that whole class of
             risk - the task's own /tr becomes a single bare path, no
             arguments, nothing for Task Scheduler to mis-split. -->
        <Component Id="AgentParams" Directory="INSTALLFOLDER" Guid="*">
          <File Id="AgentParamsIni" Source="agent-params-template.ini" Name="agent-params.ini" KeyPath="yes" />
          <IniFile Id="SetServerUrl" Directory="INSTALLFOLDER" Name="agent-params.ini" Action="createLine" Section="DeployCore" Key="ServerUrl" Value="[SERVERURL]" />
          <IniFile Id="SetEnrollToken" Directory="INSTALLFOLDER" Name="agent-params.ini" Action="addLine" Section="DeployCore" Key="EnrollToken" Value="[ENROLLTOKEN]" />
        </Component>
        <!-- The stock RustDesk client installer, fetched by CI (which has
             internet) and bundled here so the install script never needs
             outbound internet access on the target machine - only to
             DeployCore itself, which is where this .msi came from in the
             first place. See remote_agent_install.ps1 step 2 for why this
             matters: a VM the deployment pipeline just provisioned commonly
             has no internet access at all. -->
        <Component Id="RustDeskInstaller" Guid="*">
          <File Id="RustDeskMsi" Source="rustdesk-x86_64.msi" KeyPath="yes" />
        </Component>
        <!-- Separate component (one file each) so WiX can auto-generate GUIDs -
             an unversioned keypath can't share a component with other files.
             Installed next to the script so its branding step can point the
             Add/Remove Programs DisplayIcon at it (see remote_agent_install.ps1). -->
        <Component Id="BrandIcon" Guid="*">
          <File Id="BrandIco" Source="deploycore.ico" KeyPath="yes" />
        </Component>
        <!-- Branded tray companion + a per-machine Run entry so it starts in
             each user's session at logon. Cosmetic only - the headless RustDesk
             service is what actually serves remote access. -->
        <Component Id="TrayApp" Guid="*">
          <File Id="TrayExe" Source="DeployCoreTray.exe" KeyPath="yes" />
          <RegistryValue
              Root="HKLM"
              Key="Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Run"
              Name="DeployCoreRemoteAgent"
              Type="string"
              Value="&quot;[INSTALLFOLDER]DeployCoreTray.exe&quot;" />
        </Component>
      </Directory>
    </StandardDirectory>

    <Feature Id="Main">
      <ComponentRef Id="InstallScript" />
      <ComponentRef Id="RunScript" />
      <ComponentRef Id="AgentParams" />
      <ComponentRef Id="RustDeskInstaller" />
      <ComponentRef Id="BrandIcon" />
      <ComponentRef Id="TrayApp" />
    </Feature>

    <!-- Registers a Scheduled Task pointed at RunAgentInstall.cmd (bare path,
         no arguments - it reads SERVERURL/ENROLLTOKEN from agent-params.ini,
         see AgentParams above, specifically to avoid trusting Task Scheduler
         to correctly re-parse a quoted multi-argument /tr command at actual
         execution time), running as SYSTEM. /f suppresses any "already
         exists" prompt (harmless on a reinstall/repair). Deliberately does
         NOT run yet - see RunAgentTask below and this file's header comment
         for why the two are split.

         Trigger is ONSTART (with a 30s delay for networking to come up), NOT
         ONCE - confirmed necessary live: the DeployCore deployment pipeline
         does an unconditional final reboot ("rebooting to finalize
         configuration") once every app install, including this one, reports
         done - which happens fast, since installing THIS wrapper .msi is all
         provision.py actually waits on, not the agent's own real work running
         in the background task this registers. That reboot killed the task
         mid-flight on a real deployment (confirmed via its own transcript
         log: "Die Pipeline wurde beendet." mid-RustDesk-install). An ONSTART
         trigger means the task simply resumes on the next boot if that
         happens - Install-DeployCoreAgent.ps1 is written to be safely re-run
         (skips work already done, and enrollment itself is idempotent), and
         it only self-deletes this task on a fully successful run (see its
         own Remove-AgentTask calls), so a reboot mid-flight doesn't strand it
         registered-but-abandoned.

         Runs even under SKIPRUN=1 (registering a task has no live-server
         dependency) so CI's smoke test can verify this command's quoting is
         actually correct without needing a real DeployCore server. -->
    <SetProperty
        Id="RegisterAgentTask"
        Before="RegisterAgentTask"
        Sequence="execute"
        Value="&quot;[System64Folder]schtasks.exe&quot; /create /f /ru SYSTEM /sc onstart /delay 0000:30 /tn DeployCoreAgentInstall /tr &quot;[INSTALLFOLDER]RunAgentInstall.cmd&quot;" />
    <CustomAction
        Id="RegisterAgentTask"
        BinaryRef="Wix4UtilCA_X64"
        DllEntry="WixQuietExec64"
        Execute="commit"
        Impersonate="no"
        Return="check" />

    <!-- Triggers the task immediately (schtasks /run signals Task Scheduler
         and returns right away - it does NOT wait for the task to finish),
         so this custom action, and the outer MSI's own InstallExecuteSequence
         along with it, completes in moments. The task's own script (running
         detached, outside any MSI transaction) does the real work seconds
         later - the same "installed" -> "enrolled" gap the standalone
         one-liner install already has, nothing new for ManagedHost's own
         pending/enrolled UI to handle. -->
    <SetProperty
        Id="RunAgentTask"
        Before="RunAgentTask"
        Sequence="execute"
        Value="&quot;[System64Folder]schtasks.exe&quot; /run /tn DeployCoreAgentInstall" />
    <CustomAction
        Id="RunAgentTask"
        BinaryRef="Wix4UtilCA_X64"
        DllEntry="WixQuietExec64"
        Execute="commit"
        Impersonate="no"
        Return="check" />

    <InstallExecuteSequence>
      <!-- After InstallFiles, not InstallFinalize: deferred/commit actions can
           ONLY be scheduled between InstallInitialize and InstallFinalize -
           confirmed the hard way (Windows Installer Error 2762, "the action
           must be scheduled between InstallInitialize and InstallFinalize")
           when this file previously scheduled these after InstallFinalize.
           After InstallFiles specifically because RegisterAgentTask's /tr
           command references RunAgentInstall.cmd, which needs to actually
           exist on disk by then - true once InstallFiles has run.

           Condition is "NOT REMOVE", not "NOT Installed" - confirmed live as
           a real bug: `Installed` is set (non-empty) on ANY repeat install of
           a product Windows Installer already has a record of, including a
           same-version reinstall/repair after files were deleted by hand
           instead of a real uninstall - so "NOT Installed" silently skipped
           BOTH actions on every retry against a VM that had a previous
           attempt on it, with no error at all (matches "msiexec returns
           immediately, no log, nothing happens" exactly). REMOVE is only set
           to "ALL" during a genuine uninstall, which is the one case these
           actions should NOT run - "NOT REMOVE" (also true during upgrades
           via MajorUpgrade, which uninstalls the old product with REMOVE set
           mid-sequence, and true during ordinary reinstalls/repairs) is the
           standard, correct MSI idiom for "run except when uninstalling". -->
      <Custom Action="RegisterAgentTask" After="InstallFiles" Condition="NOT REMOVE" />
      <Custom Action="RunAgentTask" After="RegisterAgentTask" Condition="NOT REMOVE AND NOT SKIPRUN" />
    </InstallExecuteSequence>
  </Package>
</Wix>
